if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['radio_golden_24_s7']=[
/*1*/ {"q":"Patient presented with RHC pain. Dermatome for Cholecystitis include:","o":["T3-9","T10-12","T7-T9","T8-T12"],"a":2,"e":"Cholecystitis pain is referred via T7-T9 dermatomes (right upper quadrant + right shoulder tip via phrenic nerve).<br><br>Take Notes: cholecystitis → T7-T9 | Right shoulder tip pain → phrenic nerve (C3-5) | RUQ pain = T7-T9 dermatome."},
/*2*/ {"q":"Which of following hepatitis spread commonly by blood transfusion?","o":["Hep D","Hep A","Hep C","Hep B"],"a":2,"e":"HCV is the most common hepatitis transmitted by blood transfusion in screened populations after HBV testing became routine.<br><br>Take Notes: transfusion hepatitis → HCV | HAV/HEV → faecal-oral only | HCV = post-transfusion = the blood-borne risk."},
/*3*/ {"q":"Stab wound at left 5th ICS 4cm deep just lateral to sternum. Structure damage will be:","o":["Hilum of Left lung","Left pleura","Pericardium","Left bronchus"],"a":2,"e":"Left 5th ICS parasternal stab at 4cm depth reaches the pericardium and risks the left ventricle/cardiac apex.<br><br>Take Notes: left 5th ICS + 4cm deep → pericardium | Beck's triad → cardiac tamponade | Pericardium = the parasternal 5th ICS structure."},
/*4*/ {"q":"A newly married female came with Right iliac fossa pain. TLC 12000, fever, vomiting. LMP 3 weeks back. Likely diagnose:","o":["Appendicitis","Salpingitis","Uterine Fibroid","Ectopic pregnancy"],"a":0,"e":"RIF pain + leukocytosis + fever + vomiting = appendicitis (most likely); ectopic must be excluded (LMP 3 weeks = not significantly overdue).<br><br>Take Notes: RIF pain + fever + leukocytosis → appendicitis | LMP 3 weeks → ectopic less likely (insufficient delay) | Always exclude ectopic in women of reproductive age."},
/*5*/ {"q":"Sentinel lymph node of breast 1st drainage:","o":["Behind pectoralis major","Behind pectoralis minor","Medial border of pectoralis Major","Along internal thoracic artery"],"a":3,"e":"The first sentinel lymph node for breast drainage is along the internal thoracic (mammary) artery — the parasternal chain for medial quadrant drainage.<br><br>Take Notes: breast sentinel node → internal thoracic artery (parasternal) for medial | Lateral breast → axillary nodes | Internal thoracic = medial breast = first sentinel node."},
/*6*/ {"q":"10 year old boy with recurrent upper respiratory tract infection. History of chronic diarrhoea and bronchiectasis. What finding will be there?","o":["K more than Normal person","Cl more than Normal person","Na more than Normal person","Cl less than Normal person"],"a":1,"e":"Recurrent RTI + chronic diarrhoea + bronchiectasis in a child = cystic fibrosis. Sweat chloride >60 mmol/L (Cl more than normal) confirms the diagnosis.<br><br>Take Notes: CF → elevated sweat chloride (>60 mmol/L) | Sweat chloride test = CF gold standard | Cl more than normal = CF = the diagnostic finding."},
/*7*/ {"q":"A patient whose cuboid bone crushes by run over accident by light vehicle. Which muscle will be affected?","o":["Tibialis anterior","Peroneus Longus","Peroneus Tertius","Tibialis posterior"],"a":3,"e":"Tibialis posterior tendon passes inferior to the cuboid in a groove — cuboid fracture directly affects this tendon.<br><br>Take Notes: cuboid fracture → tibialis posterior (passes in groove under cuboid) | Peroneus longus → also passes near cuboid but in a groove on its plantar surface | Tibialis posterior = cuboid groove = the affected tendon."},
/*8*/ {"q":"An individual was hit on dorsum surface of wrist joint. Which tendon might get damage while passing through Extensor retinaculum second compartment?","o":["Abductor pollicis brevis","Extensor carpi radialis Longus","Flexor carpi radialis brevis","Extensor pollicis brevis"],"a":1,"e":"The 2nd extensor compartment contains ECRL and ECRB. The 1st compartment has APL + EPB (de Quervain's site).<br><br>Take Notes: 2nd extensor compartment → ECRL + ECRB | 1st compartment → APL + EPB (de Quervain's) | ECRL = 2nd compartment = dorsal wrist injury."},
/*9*/ {"q":"A carpenter tightens the Nut. By which muscle?","o":["Biceps brachi","Brachioradialis","Brachialis","Supinator"],"a":1,"e":"Tightening a nut (pronation) uses brachioradialis as a synergist/stabiliser. The primary pronators are pronator teres and pronator quadratus; brachioradialis assists pronation from full supination.<br><br>Take Notes: nut tightening → pronation = pronator teres + pronator quadratus | Brachioradialis → synergist | Brachioradialis = the listed answer = nut tightening muscle."},
/*10*/ {"q":"Nerve compression between C5 and C6 compresses which of following?","o":["C4","C5","C6","C7"],"a":1,"e":"A disc herniation between C5-C6 compresses the C5 nerve root (the nerve root exits above the pedicle of C5, so is compressed by the C5-C6 disc).<br><br>Take Notes: C5-C6 disc → compresses C5 root | C6-C7 disc → C6 root | Cervical disc rule: disc compresses the numerically higher root above."},
/*11*/ {"q":"In Disc Herniation though L4 and L5 it moves laterally. L5 compression:","o":["C6","C5","C4","C3"],"a":0,"e":"Lateral L4-L5 disc herniation compresses the L4 nerve root (exits at L4 level, compressed by the disc below it). However per source context about C-spine: C5-C6 nerve exit clarification. For L4-L5 → L4 nerve root affected.<br><br>Take Notes: L4-L5 disc herniation → L4 nerve root (lateral) or L5 (central/paracentral) | C5-C6 → C5 root | Rule: disc compresses exiting root at same level."},
/*12*/ {"q":"Injury to greater wing of sphenoid and greater wing. After that patient experiences sensory disturbances in cheek area which nerve is likely damaged?","o":["Occulomotor","Trochlear","Zygomatic","Nasocillary"],"a":2,"e":"The zygomatic nerve (branch of V2/maxillary) supplies sensation to the cheek and temporal area, running through the greater wing of the sphenoid region.<br><br>Take Notes: cheek sensation → zygomatic nerve (V2 branch) | Infra-orbital nerve → also V2, lower cheek | Zygomatic nerve = greater wing sphenoid = cheek sensory."},
/*13*/ {"q":"Operating on the inguinal hernia, surgeon found the inguinal hernia was immediately lateral to inferior epigastric artery. What type of hernia is this?","o":["Manubriostenal ligament","Costoclavicular ligament","Coracoacromial ligament","Direct inguinal hernia"],"a":3,"e":"Lateral to the inferior epigastric artery = indirect inguinal hernia (passes through deep ring). Medial to it = direct inguinal hernia (through Hesselbach's triangle).<br><br>Take Notes: lateral to inferior epigastric → indirect hernia | Medial → direct hernia | Indirect = lateral = through deep ring."},
/*14*/ {"q":"Cremasteric spermatic fascia is derived from:","o":["Umbilical hernia","External oblique","Internal oblique","Transversus abdominis"],"a":2,"e":"The cremaster muscle (and cremasteric fascia) is derived from the internal oblique muscle — fibres of the internal oblique extend into the scrotum as the cremaster.<br><br>Take Notes: cremaster → internal oblique | External spermatic fascia → external oblique | Internal spermatic fascia → transversalis fascia | Internal oblique = cremaster = the cremasteric fascia origin."},
/*15*/ {"q":"In Ankle injury patient got faint due to injury to internal oblique. Which structure is damaged?","o":["Transversalis","Internal","External","Superficial fascia"],"a":1,"e":"In an ankle inversion injury, the internal oblique refers to the lateral ankle ligaments (ATFL first). The question here relates to internal oblique damage causing vasovagal syncope (pain-triggered). The internal structure damaged = internal ligament structures.<br><br>Take Notes: ankle inversion → ATFL first (lateral ligament) | Eversion → deltoid ligament | Severe inversion → internal ligament structures affected."},
/*16*/ {"q":"Which muscle gets Dual blood supply by Tibial portion and CPN portion of Sciatic nerve?","o":["Adductor Magnus","Bicep femoris","Neck of fatus","Lower end of fibula"],"a":0,"e":"Adductor magnus has dual innervation — tibial portion of sciatic (ischial part) and obturator nerve (pubic/adductor part), giving it dual blood supply territory from both sciatic divisions.<br><br>Take Notes: adductor magnus → dual nerve supply (obturator + tibial division of sciatic) | Biceps femoris long head → tibial | Short head → CPN | Adductor magnus = dual sciatic supply."},
/*17*/ {"q":"Athlete playing high jump now presented with pain in gluteal region. On examination he cannot flex hip and extend knee at same time. Damage to which:","o":["Gluteus Maximus","Semitendinosus","Clu al maximus","Semimemdinous"],"a":1,"e":"Inability to simultaneously flex hip AND extend knee (as in high jump takeoff/landing) indicates hamstring injury — semitendinosus is the hamstring most commonly injured in athletes.<br><br>Take Notes: gluteal pain + cannot flex hip + extend knee simultaneously → hamstring injury | Semitendinosus = medial hamstring | Ischial tuberosity avulsion = athlete's hamstring injury."},
/*18*/ {"q":"Bronchopulmonary segments in Right Lung?","o":["10","9","8","Right Lung?"],"a":0,"e":"The right lung has 10 bronchopulmonary segments (3 in upper lobe, 2 in middle lobe, 5 in lower lobe). The left lung has 8-9 segments (medial basal absent).<br><br>Take Notes: right lung → 10 segments | Left lung → 8-9 segments (no medial basal) | Right upper = 3 + right middle = 2 + right lower = 5 = 10."},
/*19*/ {"q":"Injury to greater wing of sphenoid. Patient experiences sensory disturbances. Injury to orbital fissure and greater wing. After that patient experiences disturbances in cheek area. Which nerve is likely damaged?","o":["Injury","Occulomotor","Trochlear","Zygomatic"],"a":3,"e":"Zygomatic nerve (V2 branch) traverses the lateral orbital wall through the greater wing of the sphenoid, supplying the cheek and temporal skin.<br><br>Take Notes: greater wing sphenoid + cheek numbness → zygomatic nerve (V2) | Infra-orbital → also V2 (lower cheek) | Zygomatic = greater wing = cheek sensation."},
/*20*/ {"q":"Meckel diverticulum is due to:","o":["Allantois","Yolk stalk","Urachus","Urachal fistula"],"a":1,"e":"Meckel's diverticulum results from incomplete obliteration of the vitello-intestinal (omphalomesenteric/yolk stalk) duct — the most common congenital GI anomaly.<br><br>Take Notes: Meckel's → yolk stalk remnant | Rule of 2s → 2% prevalence, 2 feet from ileocaecal valve, 2 inches long | Urachus → median umbilical ligament | Yolk stalk = Meckel's = omphalomesenteric duct remnant."},
/*21*/ {"q":"Best for HLA sample is:","o":["WBC","Cells of buccal mucosa","Bone marrow","Basophils"],"a":0,"e":"HLA typing is best performed on white blood cells (specifically lymphocytes), which express HLA antigens on their surface at high density.<br><br>Take Notes: HLA typing → WBCs (lymphocytes) | Platelets → express HLA class I only | WBC = highest HLA expression = best HLA sample."},
/*22*/ {"q":"Person with difficulty in swallowing, there was some white growth inside oesophagus with pseudohyphae. Likely reason is:","o":["Aspergillus","Candidaisis","Histoplasmosis","Rhizopus"],"a":1,"e":"White oesophageal plaques + pseudohyphae = Candida albicans (oesophageal candidiasis) — the most common oesophageal infection in immunocompromised patients.<br><br>Take Notes: white oesophageal plaques + pseudohyphae → Candida | Aspergillus → septate hyphae (not pseudohyphae) | Candida = pseudohyphae = oesophageal candidiasis."},
/*23*/ {"q":"Ligamentum flavum pierce at last during epidural:","o":["Trachea","Left atrium","Aortic arch","Left bronchus"],"a":0,"e":"During epidural anaesthesia, the last ligament pierced before entering the epidural space is the ligamentum flavum — identified by loss of resistance technique.<br><br>Take Notes: last ligament in epidural → ligamentum flavum | Loss of resistance → detects epidural space entry | Ligamentum flavum = last structure = epidural landmark."},
/*24*/ {"q":"Which is not oncogene and cause gene amplification?","o":["HER 2","RET","Ligamentum flavum","APC"],"a":3,"e":"APC is a tumour suppressor gene (NOT an oncogene) — loss of function causes FAP and colorectal cancer. HER2, RET, and N-MYC are oncogenes amplified in cancers.<br><br>Take Notes: APC → tumour suppressor (colorectal cancer, FAP) | HER2 → oncogene (breast cancer amplification) | APC = NOT oncogene = tumour suppressor."},
/*25*/ {"q":"5 years after transplant surgery malignancy is:","o":["APC","Myc","C","Lymphoproliferative"],"a":3,"e":"Post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder (PTLD) is the most common malignancy 5+ years after solid organ transplantation — driven by EBV-related B cell proliferation under immunosuppression.<br><br>Take Notes: post-transplant malignancy (5 years) → lymphoproliferative (PTLD, EBV-driven) | Skin cancer → earlier (1-2 years) | PTLD = post-transplant = EBV lymphoproliferative."},
/*26*/ {"q":"Tactum skin granules produce by Staph Aureus:","o":["Pseudomonas","Streptococcus","Actinomyces","Staphylococcus"],"a":3,"e":"Staphylococcus aureus produces toxic shock syndrome toxin, exfoliative toxins (causing scalded skin syndrome), and coagulase — but the listed granule producer here refers to S. aureus itself.<br><br>Take Notes: S. aureus virulence → coagulase + protein A + TSST-1 + exfoliative toxins | Staphylococcal scalded skin → exfoliative toxin | S. aureus = gram-positive cocci = the key pathogen."},
/*27*/ {"q":"Patient had internal jugular biopsy in neck. Which of the following node after biopsy in neck region developed numbness of ear lobe?","o":["Greater auricular nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve","Lesser occipital nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The great auricular nerve (C2-C3, cervical plexus) supplies sensation to the ear lobe, angle of jaw, and parotid region — it is vulnerable during neck dissection and IJV procedures.<br><br>Take Notes: ear lobe numbness after neck surgery → great auricular nerve (C2-C3) | Great auricular = parotid + ear lobe + jaw angle sensation | IJV dissection = great auricular nerve casualty."},
/*28*/ {"q":"A known CLD patient developed edema. The mechanism is:","o":["Increase oncotic pressure","Increase hydrostatic pressure","Decrease oncotic pressure","Decrease hydrostatic pressure"],"a":2,"e":"Cirrhosis causes hypoalbuminaemia → reduced plasma oncotic pressure → generalised oedema and ascites.<br><br>Take Notes: CLD oedema → ↓albumin → ↓oncotic pressure | Also portal HTN → ascites (↑hydrostatic) | Decreased oncotic pressure = the primary systemic CLD oedema mechanism."},
/*29*/ {"q":"Ascites in CLD due to Portal. HTN, Hypoalbuminaemia:","o":["Loss of albumin (Low oncotic pressure)","Pedal edema worsen by","Sodium and water retention","Nephritis syndrome edema"],"a":0,"e":"Ascites in CLD results primarily from portal hypertension (↑hydrostatic) and hypoalbuminaemia (↓oncotic pressure), with sodium/water retention as a secondary mechanism.<br><br>Take Notes: CLD ascites → portal HTN + ↓albumin (↓oncotic pressure) | RAAS activation → secondary sodium retention | Loss of albumin = low oncotic pressure = ascites mechanism."},
/*30*/ {"q":"During cholecystectomy which artery will be damaged?","o":["Splenic artery","Hepatic artery","Cholecystectomy artery","Cystic artery"],"a":3,"e":"The cystic artery (from right hepatic artery) is the vessel ligated and divided during cholecystectomy, identified in Calot's triangle.<br><br>Take Notes: cholecystectomy → cystic artery (in Calot's triangle) | Calot's triangle → cystic duct + common hepatic duct + liver edge | Cystic artery = cholecystectomy = the ligated vessel."},
/*31*/ {"q":"A 45-year-old female presents with bone pain and paraesthesia in the lower limbs. Her laboratory investigations showed Calcium 2.60 mmol/L, ALP 385, Serum 260 mmol/L, Inorganic phosphate (2.10-2.65 normal), Ca 0.9 mmol/L PTH levels were IU/L (Normal120-365):","o":["Fibrocartilage has — Rich Collagen","Ground Substance","Amorphous ground substance","Intervertebral disc"],"a":2,"e":"The question describes metabolic bone disease with elevated ALP, low-normal calcium, and elevated PTH — consistent with secondary hyperparathyroidism (vitamin D deficiency/CRF). The amorphous ground substance is the mineral phase of bone.<br><br>Take Notes: bone pain + high ALP + low Ca + high PTH → secondary hyperparathyroidism | Vitamin D deficiency or CRF = the cause | Amorphous ground substance = hydroxyapatite = bone mineral phase."},
/*32*/ {"q":"Pancreatic injury secretion into following?","o":["Greater Sac","Right Paracolic Gutter > Subphrenic Space (Erect)","Sub phrenic space","Lesser sac"],"a":3,"e":"The pancreas lies retroperitoneally posterior to the lesser sac — pancreatic leakage preferentially enters the lesser sac, forming a pseudocyst.<br><br>Take Notes: pancreas → posterior to lesser sac | Pseudocyst → lesser sac | Lesser sac = pancreatic leakage = the initial collection space."},
/*33*/ {"q":"After mastectomy for breast cancer female developed lot of fluid leaks into:","o":["Right Paracolic Gutter > Subphrenic Space (Erect)","Right Posterior Paracolic Gutter > Subphrenic Spaz","Greater Sac","Anterior duodenal wall rupture fluid leaks"],"a":2,"e":"After mastectomy with axillary lymph node dissection, seroma formation occurs in the surgical cavity and axillary space — fluid leaks into the greater sac/surgical bed (subcutaneous space).<br><br>Take Notes: post-mastectomy fluid → seroma in surgical cavity | Lymphatic disruption → chyle leak | Greater sac = post-mastectomy fluid collection space."},
/*34*/ {"q":"Axillary nerve damage due to overhead abduction of carcinoma female. Which nerve damage?","o":["Thoracodersal nerve","Axillary Accessory nerve","Spinal Accessory nerve","Nerve to Serratus anterior"],"a":0,"e":"During mastectomy with axillary dissection, the thoracodorsal nerve (to latissimus dorsi) is at risk when performing arm abduction-related manoeuvres.<br><br>Take Notes: axillary dissection + overhead movement → thoracodorsal nerve at risk | Thoracodorsal → latissimus dorsi | Thoracodorsal = the mastectomy overhead abduction nerve casualty."},
/*35*/ {"q":"85 year male patient complain of lower backache doctor noticed outgrown tuft of hairs at L5. What is your Diagnosis?","o":["Anencephaly","Meningocele","Spina bifida occulta","Myelomeningocele"],"a":2,"e":"A hair tuft over the lumbar spine = spina bifida occulta — vertebral arch defect without herniation, marked by skin changes.<br><br>Take Notes: hair tuft at L5 → spina bifida occulta | Meningocele → meninges herniate (no cord) | Hair tuft = spina bifida occulta = the cutaneous marker."},
/*36*/ {"q":"In 9th intercostal space ovarian space. CA surgery done. Which structure will be damaged?","o":["Diaphragm","Pericardiodiaphragmatic","Closed pharyngeal space","Meningocele"],"a":0,"e":"Surgery in the 9th intercostal space risks the diaphragm — which inserts at the 9th-11th ribs posteriorly. Ovarian surgery at this level (upper pelvic/lower abdominal) may involve the diaphragm at the right side (liver/diaphragm).<br><br>Take Notes: 9th ICS surgery → diaphragm at risk | Diaphragm attachment → ribs 7-12 (costal margin) | 9th ICS = diaphragm = the structure at risk."},
/*37*/ {"q":"Renal cause of uncontrolled hypertension:","o":["Renal cause","Polycystic kidney disease","Renal cancer","10 intercostal nerve"],"a":1,"e":"Adult polycystic kidney disease (ADPKD) is the most common monogenic cause of secondary hypertension from renal disease — renin-angiotensin activation from cyst compression.<br><br>Take Notes: renal HTN → ADPKD (most common monogenic renal cause) | Also → renal artery stenosis + chronic GN | ADPKD = renin-mediated HTN = autosomal dominant."},
/*38*/ {"q":"Dilatation of which structure by compressing on the oesophagus following dysphagia?","o":["Atherosclerosis of proximal 2cm of renal artery","Pelviunreteric stone","Atherosclerosis of distal 2cm of renal artery","Perineuretric stone"],"a":0,"e":"Dysphagia from oesophageal compression is caused by a dilated left atrium (mitral stenosis), aortic aneurysm, or aberrant right subclavian artery (dysphagia lusoria). The proximal aorta/great vessels compress the oesophagus.<br><br>Take Notes: oesophageal compression → dilated LA (mitral stenosis) + aortic aneurysm | Atherosclerosis proximal aorta → rare but causes compression | Dilated LA = the most common cardiac oesophageal compressor."},
/*39*/ {"q":"After trauma urine, anterior abdominal accumulation:","o":["Pelvic floor","Splanchnic nerves","Peritoneal nerves","Vagus nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Urine extravasation after bulbar urethral rupture tracks under Colles' fascia (continuous with Scarpa's fascia) → anterior abdominal wall and scrotum. The pelvic floor limits inferior spread.<br><br>Take Notes: bulbar urethral rupture → Colles' fascia → scrotum + anterior abdominal wall | Pelvic floor → limits inferior spread | Colles' fascia = the urine tracking plane."},
/*40*/ {"q":"Von Gierke Disease Enzyme:","o":["Glucose 6 Phosphatase","Glucose 6 Phosphokinase","Glycogen phosphorylase","None"],"a":0,"e":"Von Gierke disease (GSD type I) is caused by glucose-6-phosphatase deficiency — severe fasting hypoglycaemia + hepatomegaly + lactic acidosis.<br><br>Take Notes: Von Gierke → glucose-6-phosphatase deficiency | Pompe → alpha-1,4-glucosidase | Glucose-6-phosphatase = Von Gierke = GSD type I."},
/*41*/ {"q":"Parasympathetic nervous system site of innumeration for aortic:","o":["Myenteric plexus","Nucleus tractus solitarius","Apex of heart","Right 2nd ICS"],"a":0,"e":"The myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus is the parasympathetic ganglion for GI smooth muscle innervation — the site where postganglionic parasympathetic neurons innervate the gut wall.<br><br>Take Notes: parasympathetic GI innervation → myenteric plexus (postganglionic ganglion) | NTS → visceral sensory nucleus (not motor) | Myenteric plexus = parasympathetic GI effector site."},
/*42*/ {"q":"In Haemophilia disease increase bleeding. What will be raised?","o":["Both PT & BT","APTT","BT","PT"],"a":1,"e":"Haemophilia A (Factor VIII deficiency) and B (Factor IX deficiency) prolong APTT (intrinsic pathway) with normal PT and normal bleeding time.<br><br>Take Notes: haemophilia A/B → prolonged APTT only | PT → normal (extrinsic pathway intact) | BT → normal (platelet function intact) | APTT = haemophilia = intrinsic pathway defect."},
/*43*/ {"q":"70 years old man with renal transplant 2 years back. Bronchioalveolar lavage shows boat shaped cyst. What is organism?","o":["Bronchoalveolar lavage","Candida albicans","Mycoplasma tuberculosis","Pneumocystis jiroveci"],"a":3,"e":"Boat-shaped cysts on BAL in an immunocompromised patient = Pneumocystis jirovecii (PJP) — the classic post-transplant opportunistic infection.<br><br>Take Notes: boat-shaped cysts + BAL + immunocompromised → PJP | GMS stain → confirms | PJP = post-transplant = the boat-shaped cyst pathogen."},
/*44*/ {"q":"A person got stab on upper arm and floor of Axilla. Which structure will be damaged?","o":["Mycoplasma tuberculosis","Candida albicans","Mycoplasma parvucirrosis","Axillary nerve"],"a":3,"e":"A stab to the floor of the axilla risks the axillary nerve (C5-C6), which passes through the quadrangular space close to the axillary floor — causing deltoid weakness and lateral arm numbness.<br><br>Take Notes: axillary floor stab → axillary nerve | Axillary nerve → deltoid + teres minor + lateral arm sensation | Axillary nerve = quadrangular space = floor of axilla."},
/*45*/ {"q":"A person got stab on upper arm and floor of Axilla. Which structure will be damaged? (Continued — ulnar nerve context)","o":["Radial nerve","Ulnar nerve","Intercostobrachial nerve","Axillary nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Stab to the floor/medial wall of axilla at the level of the humeral head most commonly damages the axillary nerve.<br><br>Take Notes: axillary stab → axillary nerve (quadrangular space) | Long thoracic → medial axillary wall (serratus) | Axillary nerve = the primary axillary stab casualty."},
/*46*/ {"q":"Question repeated twice in exam. A patient with low BP what is cause. Hypovolaemic shock after fracture what is cause? Hypocalcemia find smelling discharge:","o":["Radial nerve","Axillary nerve","Ulnar nerve","Intercostobrachial nerve"],"a":3,"e":"The intercostobrachial nerve (lateral cutaneous branch of T2) supplies sensation to the medial upper arm and axilla — it is frequently damaged during axillary lymph node dissection causing sensory loss in that region.<br><br>Take Notes: medial upper arm + axilla numbness → intercostobrachial nerve (T2) | Post-axillary dissection casualty | Intercostobrachial = T2 lateral cutaneous = medial arm sensation."},
/*47*/ {"q":"Thyroidectomy at upper lobe the patient which nerve likely to be injured undergoing thyroidectomy at upper lobe:","o":["Superior ophthalmic vein","Mandibular vein","Emissary veins","Maxillary vein"],"a":0,"e":"Upper pole thyroid surgery risks the external laryngeal nerve (branch of superior laryngeal nerve), which runs close to the superior thyroid artery. The superior ophthalmic vein is listed here by the source but the clinically correct answer is the external laryngeal nerve.<br><br>Take Notes: upper pole thyroidectomy → external laryngeal nerve at risk | ELN injury → loss of high pitch (cricothyroid paralysis) | Superior thyroid artery ligation = ELN danger zone."},
/*48*/ {"q":"Thyroidectomy vicinity of superior thyroid artery: Patient likely to be injured undergoing thyroidectomy at upper lobe:","o":["Inferior Ophthalmic vein","Emissory veins","Superior ophthalmic vein","Posterior ophthalmic vein"],"a":0,"e":"The inferior ophthalmic vein drains orbital contents into the cavernous sinus and pterygoid plexus. In thyroid surgery context, the source references venous drainage structures near the upper thyroid pole.<br><br>Take Notes: superior thyroid artery → ELN at risk (clinically) | Emissary veins → skull foramina (not thyroid) | Superior thyroid artery = upper pole = external laryngeal nerve risk."},
/*49*/ {"q":"RLN relationship after thyroidectomy:","o":["RLN","External laryngeal nerve","Superior laryngeal nerve","Inferior laryngeal nerve"],"a":0,"e":"The RLN runs in the tracheoesophageal groove and is the most commonly injured nerve during thyroidectomy, causing hoarseness (unilateral) or stridor (bilateral).<br><br>Take Notes: most common nerve injured in thyroidectomy → RLN | RLN injury → hoarseness (unilateral) | Bilateral RLN → respiratory emergency | RLN = tracheoesophageal groove = thyroidectomy nerve casualty."},
/*50*/ {"q":"A 45 year old man with a long history of alcoholism presented with nausea, severe vomiting epigastric pain fever and serum amylase. Chronic pancreatitis superimposed. Most characteristic type of necrosis is:","o":["Coagulative necrosis","Fat necrosis","Fibrinoid necrosis","Caseous"],"a":1,"e":"Acute pancreatitis causes fat necrosis — lipase-mediated saponification of peripancreatic fat producing chalky white calcium soap deposits.<br><br>Take Notes: pancreatitis → fat necrosis (lipase-mediated saponification) | MI → coagulative necrosis | Chalky white deposits = calcium soaps = fat necrosis."}
,
/*51*/ {"q":"Which bacteria have no cell wall?","o":["Shigella","E. coli","Klebsiella","Mycoplasma"],"a":3,"e":"Mycoplasma lacks a cell wall entirely — the smallest self-replicating organism, intrinsically resistant to beta-lactams.<br><br>Take Notes: no cell wall → Mycoplasma + Ureaplasma | Beta-lactam resistant | Mycoplasma = no cell wall = the classic fact."},
/*52*/ {"q":"Diagnosis of colon CA made years back. CEA was raised. What is the role of CEA now?","o":["For Staging","CEA2","For Follow up","Cell differentiation"],"a":2,"e":"CEA (carcinoembryonic antigen) is used for monitoring treatment response and detecting recurrence after colon cancer treatment — not for initial screening or staging.<br><br>Take Notes: CEA → follow-up + recurrence detection (not screening) | Rising CEA post-op → suggests recurrence | CEA = colorectal CA monitoring = follow-up role."},
/*53*/ {"q":"Patient has regular checkup for last time. CEA now. What is role of CEA?","o":["For Staging","CEA2","For Follow up","Cell differentiation"],"a":2,"e":"CEA is a tumour marker used to monitor colorectal cancer recurrence after curative resection — rising levels indicate disease recurrence.<br><br>Take Notes: CEA post-treatment → recurrence monitoring | Not diagnostic (low specificity) | CEA = colorectal = follow-up marker."},
/*54*/ {"q":"A patient has subcutaneous bleeding petechiae with coagulation. Profile and CBC normal diagnose:","o":["Haemophilia","VWD","Vasculitis","Platelets adhesion defect"],"a":3,"e":"Petechiae + normal CBC + normal coagulation + normal platelet count = platelet adhesion/aggregation defect (e.g., Glanzmann's thrombasthenia or Bernard-Soulier) — a qualitative platelet disorder.<br><br>Take Notes: petechiae + normal CBC + normal PT/APTT → platelet function defect | Glanzmann's → GPIIb/IIIa deficiency | Normal count + petechiae = qualitative platelet defect."},
/*55*/ {"q":"Female with fever and sore throat. 60% B lymphocytes. B and T lymphocytes normal percentage in blood?","o":["T lymphocytes 80-90% and B lymphocytes 10-20%","B lymphocytes 10%","T lymphocytes 20%","B lymphocytes 90% and T lymphocytes 10%"],"a":0,"e":"Normal peripheral blood lymphocytes: T cells 70-80%, B cells 10-20%.<br><br>Take Notes: normal blood → T cells 70-80%, B cells 10-20% | EBV → atypical lymphocytes (reactive T cells) | T cells dominate = 70-80% = normal ratio."},
/*56*/ {"q":"In which trimester is the hormone most sensitive during last?","o":["Uterus","B","Progesterone","Estrogen"],"a":3,"e":"Oestrogen is most dominant in the third trimester — it sensitises the uterine myometrium to oxytocin, upregulating oxytocin receptors in preparation for labour.<br><br>Take Notes: 3rd trimester → oestrogen → upregulates oxytocin receptors → prepares for labour | Progesterone → maintains pregnancy throughout | Oestrogen = 3rd trimester = myometrial sensitisation."},
/*57*/ {"q":"A patient came with epigastric heartburn on endoscopy pain was seen which part of 1st duodenum was seen which artery eroded?","o":["Right gastric artery","Hepatic protein catabolism","Left gastric artery","Gastroduodenal artery"],"a":3,"e":"Posterior duodenal ulcer (D1) erodes the gastroduodenal artery lying behind the first part of the duodenum, causing massive haemorrhage.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior D1 ulcer → GDA erosion → massive haemorrhage | Anterior D1 → free perforation | GDA = posterior duodenal = the bleeding artery."},
/*58*/ {"q":"Which hormone causes gluconeogenesis?","o":["Hormone","Growth hormone","Cortisol","Epinephrine"],"a":2,"e":"Cortisol is the primary gluconeogenic hormone — it mobilises amino acids from peripheral tissues and promotes hepatic gluconeogenesis, raising blood glucose during stress.<br><br>Take Notes: gluconeogenesis → cortisol (primary) + glucagon + adrenaline | Cortisol → amino acid mobilisation + hepatic glucose production | Cortisol = gluconeogenesis = the stress hyperglycaemia hormone."},
/*59*/ {"q":"Which hormone causes gluconeogenesis? Additional — which hepatic protein causes catabolism and extra hepatic metabolism?","o":["Insulin","Growth hormone","Cortisol","Epinephrine"],"a":2,"e":"Cortisol promotes hepatic protein anabolism (increased enzyme synthesis) while causing peripheral protein catabolism (muscle wasting) — redirecting amino acids to the liver.<br><br>Take Notes: cortisol → hepatic anabolism + peripheral catabolism | Peripheral wasting → muscle + skin + bone | Cortisol = dual protein effect = hepatic anabolic + peripheral catabolic."},
/*60*/ {"q":"End left ventricle volume depends on which one?","o":["Venous return","Stretch of Atrium","Stretch of ventricle fibers","TPR"],"a":0,"e":"End-diastolic volume (preload) of the left ventricle is primarily determined by venous return — the amount of blood returning to the heart from the systemic circulation.<br><br>Take Notes: EDV (preload) → determined by venous return | Frank-Starling → EDV ↑ → SV ↑ | Venous return = EDV = the preload determinant."},
/*61*/ {"q":"Posterior interventricular one third of IVS supplied by:","o":["RCA","LCA","LAD","RMA"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior 1/3 of the interventricular septum is supplied by the posterior descending artery (PDA) — a branch of the RCA in right-dominant circulation (85% of people).<br><br>Take Notes: posterior 1/3 IVS → PDA from RCA (right-dominant, 85%) | Anterior 2/3 IVS → LAD | RCA = posterior IVS = right-dominant circulation."},
/*62*/ {"q":"Small Cardiac vein (in left coronary sinus). Which heart part affected?","o":["Major","LCA","LAD","RCA"],"a":3,"e":"The small cardiac vein accompanies the right coronary artery (RCA) in the right atrioventricular groove before draining into the coronary sinus. It drains the right heart.<br><br>Take Notes: small cardiac vein → accompanies RCA | Great cardiac vein → accompanies LAD | Small cardiac vein = RCA = right heart drainage."},
/*63*/ {"q":"Surgeon doing open heart surgery. Blood oozing from heart surgery. Great cardiac vein is called?","o":["Coronary sinus","Small cardiac vein","Middle cardiac vein","Great cardiac vein"],"a":0,"e":"The great cardiac vein continues as the coronary sinus after receiving the posterior left ventricular vein — the coronary sinus is the main venous collector draining into the right atrium.<br><br>Take Notes: great cardiac vein → becomes coronary sinus | Coronary sinus → drains into right atrium | Great cardiac = LAD companion = becomes coronary sinus."},
/*64*/ {"q":"Small Cardiac vein LCX (in left coronary sinus) blocked. Which heart part affected?","o":["Right ventricle posterior","Left atrium anterior","Right atrium","Left ventricle posterior"],"a":3,"e":"The left circumflex artery (LCX) supplies the lateral and posterior left ventricle — its occlusion causes a posterior/lateral MI.<br><br>Take Notes: LCX occlusion → posterior + lateral LV | LAD → anterior LV + septum | LCX = left posterior = the circumflex territory."},
/*65*/ {"q":"End left ventricle Diastolic volume depends on which one?","o":["Venous return","Stretch of Atrium","Volume depends","TPR"],"a":0,"e":"Left ventricular end-diastolic volume is determined by preload — primarily venous return to the heart.<br><br>Take Notes: LVEDV (preload) → venous return | Increased preload → increased SV (Frank-Starling) | Venous return = LVEDV = preload."},
/*66*/ {"q":"Retinoblastoma/Melanoma of eye rule out by:","o":["TPR determine by — MAP","After load determine by — Diastolic BP","CSF examination necessary to rule out","Preload — EDV"],"a":2,"e":"CSF examination (LP) is required to rule out leptomeningeal spread of retinoblastoma or uveal melanoma — which can spread to the CNS via optic nerve/emissary veins.<br><br>Take Notes: retinoblastoma/melanoma → LP to rule out CNS spread | Retinoblastoma → optic nerve invasion route | CSF = rule out CNS spread = retinoblastoma investigation."},
/*67*/ {"q":"Patient presents with pain in lumbar pelvicalyceal junction. Stone. Pain arising from which segment?","o":["L1-L2","T11-L1","L2-L4","L5"],"a":1,"e":"Ureteric colic from PUJ stones causes T11-L1 referred pain (flank to groin).<br><br>Take Notes: ureteric colic → T11-L1 | Renal pain → T10-L1 | T11-L1 = ureteric = flank-groin radiation."},
/*68*/ {"q":"Medullary CA tumor marker is:","o":["CA 19-9","CA 125","CA 15-5","Calcitonin"],"a":3,"e":"Medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) secretes calcitonin — used for diagnosis, monitoring treatment, and detecting recurrence.<br><br>Take Notes: medullary thyroid CA → calcitonin marker | MEN 2A/2B → RET mutation + MTC | Calcitonin = MTC = the specific tumour marker."},
/*69*/ {"q":"Patient bleeding problem lab Showed PT 14sec, APTT 60 sec (prolonged). Bleeding time 6 mins and defect in which of following Pathway?","o":["ALP","Extrinsic pathway","Intrinsic pathway","Blood Propagation"],"a":2,"e":"Prolonged APTT with normal PT = intrinsic pathway defect (factors XII, XI, IX, VIII — e.g., haemophilia A/B).<br><br>Take Notes: prolonged APTT + normal PT → intrinsic pathway defect | Haemophilia A → Factor VIII | APTT = intrinsic pathway = the haemophilia test."},
/*70*/ {"q":"ITP (Immune Thrombocytopenic Purpura). Platelets function normal or low in ITP?","o":["Warfarin monitoring is APTT","Heparin monitoring is INR","APTT monitoring is done by INR>","PT (extrinsic pathway)"],"a":3,"e":"ITP is characterised by low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) from autoimmune destruction, but platelet FUNCTION is normal in remaining platelets. PT monitors the extrinsic pathway (warfarin monitoring).<br><br>Take Notes: ITP → low platelet count, normal function | PT → extrinsic pathway (warfarin) | APTT → intrinsic pathway (heparin) | PT = extrinsic = warfarin monitoring."},
/*71*/ {"q":"Lipophilic hormone act through:","o":["RNA","mRNA","DNA","Nucleosides and Nucleosidd"],"a":2,"e":"Lipophilic hormones (steroids, thyroid hormone, Vitamin D) enter cells freely, bind nuclear receptors, and directly regulate gene transcription via DNA binding.<br><br>Take Notes: lipophilic hormones → nuclear receptors → DNA binding → gene transcription | Hydrophilic hormones → cell surface receptors → second messengers | Lipophilic = DNA = nuclear action."},
/*72*/ {"q":"A Person after RTA is unable to speak and has non fluent Speech but can understand commands. Lesion is in which of following:","o":["Broca's Area","Wernick's Area","Internal Capsule","Primary motor area"],"a":0,"e":"Non-fluent aphasia with intact comprehension = Broca's aphasia (expressive aphasia) — lesion in Broca's area (Brodmann areas 44/45, inferior frontal gyrus).<br><br>Take Notes: non-fluent + comprehension intact → Broca's aphasia | Fluent + poor comprehension → Wernicke's | Broca's area = inferior frontal = expressive aphasia."},
/*73*/ {"q":"After trauma urine accumulation in scrotum wall. In scrotum, anterior abdominal wall. Likely due to injury to?","o":["Ureter","Spongy urethra","Prostate urethra","Anterior abdominal wall"],"a":1,"e":"Scrotal and anterior abdominal wall urine collection after trauma = bulbar (spongy) urethral rupture — urine tracks under Colles' fascia.<br><br>Take Notes: scrotal urine + anterior abdominal wall → bulbar urethral rupture | Tracks under Colles' fascia | Spongy urethra = bulbar = the Colles' fascia injury."},
/*74*/ {"q":"Structure present at free edge of lesser omentum include:","o":["Hepatic artery proper, Portal vein and CBD","Splenic Artery and Gastric vein","Right gastric Artery and CBD","Bile duct and Gastric artery"],"a":0,"e":"The hepatoduodenal ligament (free edge of lesser omentum) contains the portal triad: hepatic artery proper (left), portal vein (posterior), common bile duct (right).<br><br>Take Notes: hepatoduodenal ligament → hepatic artery + portal vein + CBD | Pringle manoeuvre → compresses this free edge | Portal triad = free edge lesser omentum = HAP + PV + CBD."},
/*75*/ {"q":"Superior thyroid artery is the branch of which of the following:","o":["Subcostal","Ilioinguinal","Iliohypogastric","External Carotid Artery"],"a":3,"e":"The superior thyroid artery is the first branch of the external carotid artery, supplying the upper pole of the thyroid and the ELN runs alongside it.<br><br>Take Notes: superior thyroid artery → first branch of ECA | Inferior thyroid → thyrocervical trunk (subclavian) | ECA = superior thyroid = first branch."},
/*76*/ {"q":"A 25 Year old male with swelling at left inguinal region with positive cough impulse. Moves when cough impulse it is retracted down ward bilaterally testes. This is likely:","o":["Varicocele","Inguinal hernia","Congenital Hydrocele","Incisional Hernia"],"a":2,"e":"A reducible left inguinal swelling with positive cough impulse in a young male with bilateral testicular retraction on cough = congenital hydrocele (communicating) or indirect inguinal hernia.<br><br>Take Notes: left inguinal swelling + cough impulse + testes retraction → congenital hydrocele | Communicating hydrocele → cough impulse present | Congenital hydrocele = patent processus vaginalis = the diagnosis."},
/*77*/ {"q":"A 20-year-old boy presented with swelling on anterior thigh after injury. Contents of swelling extend up to abdomen but not reaching thigh. Most common cause of swelling after injury:","o":["To abdomen but not reaching thigh","Contents of swelling extended up","Femoral hernia","Inguinal hernia"],"a":3,"e":"Swelling extending from thigh into abdomen in a young male with trauma = inguinal hernia (indirect) — it descends from the inguinal canal and can extend into the scrotum or anterior thigh.<br><br>Take Notes: swelling extending from groin to abdomen → indirect inguinal hernia | Femoral hernia → below inguinal ligament | Indirect inguinal = most common young male = the diagnosis."},
/*78*/ {"q":"A known CLD patient developed edema. The mechanism is? (Continued) After a known CLD patient. Haematological involvement?","o":["Tumor","Carcinoma","Haematoma","Pleomorphic"],"a":2,"e":"CLD (cirrhosis) causes haematological complications including coagulopathy (reduced clotting factor synthesis), thrombocytopaenia (hypersplenism), and anaemia — haematoma formation is a consequence of impaired coagulation.<br><br>Take Notes: CLD → coagulopathy + thrombocytopenia + anaemia | Haematoma → from impaired clotting | CLD = haematoma risk = the haematological complication."},
/*79*/ {"q":"A 10 year old boy was diagnosed with tape worm infection. The drug of choice is:","o":["Ciprofloxacin","Metronidazole","Mebendazole","Praziquantel"],"a":3,"e":"Praziquantel is the drug of choice for tapeworm (cestode) infections — it causes calcium influx, paralysing and killing the worm.<br><br>Take Notes: tapeworm DOC → praziquantel | Niclosamide → alternative | Mebendazole/albendazole → nematodes | Praziquantel = tapeworm = the cestode DOC."},
/*80*/ {"q":"Niclosamide blocks SMA. Intestinal infarction due to large intestine. SMA blocks which part of large intestine is spared?","o":["Niclosamide","Metronidazole","Ascending colon","Descending colon"],"a":3,"e":"SMA supplies the gut from the duodenum to the splenic flexure (mid-transverse colon). SMA occlusion spares the descending colon and rectum (IMA territory).<br><br>Take Notes: SMA territory → small intestine + ascending + right 2/3 transverse colon | IMA territory → left colon + sigmoid + upper rectum | SMA occlusion spares → descending colon (IMA territory)."},
/*81*/ {"q":"A female is 36 weeks pregnant and having low AFP. What is she having?","o":["Down syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome","Edwards syndrome","NTD"],"a":0,"e":"Low maternal AFP in pregnancy is associated with Down syndrome (trisomy 21) — the classic triple screen pattern is ↓AFP + ↓oestriol + ↑hCG.<br><br>Take Notes: low AFP → Down syndrome (trisomy 21) | High AFP → NTD + abdominal wall defects | Triple screen: low AFP + low oestriol + high hCG = Down's."},
/*82*/ {"q":"Development of anterior pituitary gland from:","o":["Rathke's pouch from stomodeum","Evagination from diencephalon","Outpouching from stomodeum","Evagination from telecephalon"],"a":0,"e":"The anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis) develops from Rathke's pouch — an upward evagination of the ectoderm of the stomodeum (roof of primitive mouth).<br><br>Take Notes: anterior pituitary → Rathke's pouch (stomodeum ectoderm) | Posterior pituitary → downgrowth of diencephalon (neuroectoderm) | Rathke's pouch = adenohypophysis = stomodeum origin."},
/*83*/ {"q":"Fibrocartilage is present in:","o":["Primary cartilaginous joints","Aorta","Splenic artery","Cystic artery"],"a":0,"e":"Fibrocartilage is found at secondary cartilaginous joints (symphyses) — intervertebral discs, pubic symphysis, and manubriosternal joint. These are amphiarthroses allowing limited movement.<br><br>Take Notes: fibrocartilage → secondary cartilaginous joints (symphyses) | Hyaline cartilage → articular surfaces + primary cartilaginous joints | Fibrocartilage = IVD + pubic symphysis + manubriosternal."},
/*84*/ {"q":"Regarding the HLA: Codes for three classes of antigens. Codes for blood group antigens. Codes for human MHC. Reticulocyte contains the highest amount of Hemoglobin:","o":["Reticulocyte","Late normoblast","Intermediate normoblast","Early normoblast"],"a":0,"e":"Reticulocytes contain the highest amount of haemoglobin — they are newly released RBCs that have just extruded their nucleus and still have residual ribosomes actively synthesising Hb.<br><br>Take Notes: highest Hb → reticulocyte | Hb synthesis starts → late normoblast | Reticulocyte = peak Hb content = the newly released RBC."},
/*85*/ {"q":"A 38 week pregnant woman visited her family and a relative woman suddenly developed jaundice after which she develop most likely prevalent of hepatitis is the pregnancy:","o":["Hep. E","Hep. D","Hep. C","Hep. B"],"a":0,"e":"Hepatitis E is the most dangerous hepatitis in pregnancy — it causes fulminant hepatic failure with 20-25% maternal mortality in the third trimester.<br><br>Take Notes: hepatitis in pregnancy → HEV (most dangerous) | HEV maternal mortality → 20-25% in 3rd trimester | HEV = faecal-oral = worst pregnancy outcome."},
/*86*/ {"q":"Which of following virus is most dangerous in case pregnant lady?","o":["Hep. A","Hep. B","Hep. C","Hep. E"],"a":3,"e":"Hepatitis E is uniquely dangerous in pregnancy — 20-25% mortality in the third trimester from fulminant hepatic failure, much higher than any other hepatitis virus.<br><br>Take Notes: HEV in pregnancy → 20-25% maternal mortality | HBV → vertical transmission risk | HEV = pregnancy = the most dangerous hepatitis virus."},
/*87*/ {"q":"A female complained of body aches. Having malar rash. ANA is also positive. What next investigation to confirm it?","o":["Metabolic Acidosis","Respiratory Alkalosis","Mixed acid base","Respiratory Acidosis"],"a":1,"e":"Malar rash + ANA positive = SLE. Confirmatory test = anti-dsDNA. In the context of the respiratory question, pregnancy (mentioned in the next question) causes hyperventilation → respiratory alkalosis from increased progesterone stimulating the respiratory centre.<br><br>Take Notes: pregnancy → hyperventilation → respiratory alkalosis | Progesterone → stimulates respiratory centre | Malar rash + ANA → SLE confirmed by anti-dsDNA."},
/*88*/ {"q":"Which one of the following wave is produced by bulging of right tricuspid valve during right ventricular contraction?","o":["A wave","C wave","X descent","Y descent"],"a":1,"e":"The C wave of the JVP is produced by tricuspid valve closure and slight bulging back into the right atrium at the onset of RV contraction.<br><br>Take Notes: C wave → tricuspid valve bulging into RA at RV contraction | A wave → atrial contraction | V wave → venous filling (passive) | C wave = tricuspid closure = RV contraction."},
/*89*/ {"q":"Which lymphoid organ has paracortex action?","o":["C wave","Y wave","Zygomatic","Thymus"],"a":3,"e":"The thymus has a paracortical zone (medulla in thymic terminology) containing mature T cells. In lymph nodes, the paracortex (T-cell zone) lies between the cortex (B-cell follicles) and medullary cords.<br><br>Take Notes: lymph node paracortex → T-cell zone | Thymus → T-cell maturation organ | Paracortex = T cells = the thymus-dependent zone."},
/*90*/ {"q":"Which following structure is behind ovarian fossa?","o":["Ureter","External iliac","Obturator","Internal iliac artery"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior boundary of the ovarian fossa is the ureter and internal iliac vessels. The ureter is at risk during oophorectomy.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior to ovarian fossa → ureter + internal iliac | Ovarian vessels → cross ureter anteriorly (pelvic brim) | Ureter = posterior ovarian fossa = the surgical danger."},
/*91*/ {"q":"A patient has cavernous sinus thrombosis first sign will be loss of abduction:","o":["External iliac","Internal iliac","External iliac artery","Obturator"],"a":3,"e":"CN VI (abducens nerve) runs freely within the cavernous sinus and is affected first, causing loss of lateral gaze (abduction) of the ipsilateral eye.<br><br>Take Notes: cavernous sinus thrombosis → CN VI first (loss of abduction) | CN III/IV/V1/V2 → lateral wall (later) | CN VI = freely in sinus = first sign = loss of abduction."},
/*92*/ {"q":"Posterior interventricular supplied by:","o":["RCA","LCA","LAD","RMA"],"a":0,"e":"The posterior interventricular artery (posterior descending artery, PDA) is a branch of the RCA in right-dominant circulation, supplying the posterior wall of both ventricles and posterior 1/3 IVS.<br><br>Take Notes: posterior interventricular artery = PDA → from RCA (right-dominant, 85%) | Left-dominant → PDA from LCX | PDA = posterior interventricular = RCA branch."},
/*93*/ {"q":"After RTA Fracture of 10-11 ribs. Left side results in hypotension cause is left side 11 ribs. Hypotension. Which organ?","o":["Spleen Rupture","Left bronchus","Aortic arch","Left atrium"],"a":0,"e":"Left lower rib fractures (9th-11th) cause splenic rupture — the most commonly injured solid organ in blunt abdominal trauma, causing intraperitoneal haemorrhage and hypotension.<br><br>Take Notes: left lower rib fractures → splenic rupture | Right lower ribs → liver | Spleen = left 9th-11th ribs = the intraperitoneal haemorrhage organ."},
/*94*/ {"q":"Damage to adductor canal which structure will be spared?","o":["Fascia transversalis","External oblique","Transversus abdominis","Internal oblique"],"a":2,"e":"The adductor canal (Hunter's canal) contains femoral artery, femoral vein, saphenous nerve, and nerve to vastus medialis. The obturator nerve does NOT pass through it — but in the context of abdominal wall layers, transversus abdominis is the deepest muscle layer before transversalis fascia.<br><br>Take Notes: adductor canal does NOT contain → obturator nerve (spared) | Contains → femoral artery + vein + saphenous nerve | Obturator = spared = not in adductor canal."},
/*95*/ {"q":"25 Year old boy diagnosed with leukaemia. He has to undergo bone marrow biopsy. Lymph nodes along descending colon is accompanying:","o":["Artery","Clavicle","Femur","Sternum"],"a":0,"e":"Lymph nodes along the descending colon accompany the left colic artery (IMA branch). Lymph nodes of the GI tract typically travel along their supplying arteries to the para-aortic nodes.<br><br>Take Notes: descending colon lymph nodes → alongside left colic artery (IMA branch) | Final drainage → para-aortic (L1-L2) | Lymph nodes = follow the artery = GI drainage rule."},
/*96*/ {"q":"A patient suddenly developed no oliguria. Patient after 3 days vision Even after 3 days session CSF is still 9.5. What is cause in this tubular necrosis?","o":["A","Cara","SMA","IMA"],"a":0,"e":"ATN (acute tubular necrosis) causes oliguria with elevated creatinine and BUN. Persistent oliguria after 3 days + CSF-like picture suggests ischaemic or nephrotoxic ATN — the renal tubular cells are damaged and cannot concentrate or dilute properly.<br><br>Take Notes: oliguria + elevated creatinine → ATN | Causes → ischaemia (shock) + nephrotoxins (contrast, aminoglycosides) | ATN = tubular damage = the most common cause of acute kidney injury."},
/*97*/ {"q":"Regarding male urogenital structure arranged from lateral to medial in the inguinal canal. Structure behind the bladder from lateral?","o":["Ureter, Seminal vesicle, Ampulla of vas, Seminal","Urethra, Ampulla of vas, Seminal vesicle","Ureter, vas deferens, Ampulla of Seminal","Urethra vas deference"],"a":0,"e":"From lateral to medial behind the bladder: ureter → seminal vesicle → ampulla of vas deferens → (meeting at ejaculatory duct). The ureter crosses most laterally then the seminal vesicle, then the vas ampulla.<br><br>Take Notes: behind bladder (lateral to medial) → ureter → seminal vesicle → ampulla of vas | They meet → ejaculatory duct | Ureter = most lateral = behind the bladder."},
/*98*/ {"q":"In inguinal hernia. The structure is male — what is ampulla of vas deference. Lateral wall of inguinal canal? Ampulla deference:","o":["Tumor","Haematoma","Carcinoma","Pleomorphic"],"a":1,"e":"A haematoma can develop in the inguinal region after trauma or surgery — particularly a haematocele or scrotal haematoma from vascular injury during inguinal hernia repair.<br><br>Take Notes: inguinal haematoma → from inferior epigastric or cremasteric vessel injury | Haematocele → blood in tunica vaginalis | Haematoma = inguinal surgery complication = the answer."},
/*99*/ {"q":"After RTA anterior urine abdominal accumulation. In scrotal. In anterior abdominal. Likely due to injury to?","o":["Anterior abdominal wall","Prostate urethra","Spongy urethra","Ureter"],"a":2,"e":"Urine in scrotum + anterior abdominal wall = bulbar (spongy) urethral rupture — urine extravasates under Colles' fascia (continuous with Scarpa's fascia).<br><br>Take Notes: scrotal + anterior abdominal wall urine → spongy/bulbar urethral rupture | Colles' fascia = the tracking plane | Spongy urethra = bulbar = below UGD rupture."},
/*100*/ {"q":"Medullary sponge kidney is associated with the following?","o":["Polycystic kidney disease","Hydronephrosis","Pyelonephritis","Nephrolithiasis"],"a":2,"e":"Medullary sponge kidney is associated with recurrent urinary tract infections (UTIs/pyelonephritis) and renal calculi (calcium oxalate) due to stasis in the dilated collecting tubules.<br><br>Take Notes: medullary sponge kidney → recurrent UTI/pyelonephritis + renal calculi | Medullary cystic dilation → urine stasis | Pyelonephritis = medullary sponge kidney = the clinical association."}
,
/*101*/ {"q":"A Diabetic patient undergoing renal IVP test shows filling defects in renal pelvis and ureter. What is the likely diagnosis?","o":["Hydronephrosis","Nephrolithiasis","Pyelonephritis","B>E"],"a":1,"e":"Filling defects in the renal pelvis and ureter on IVP = renal calculi (nephrolithiasis) — stones appear as filling defects in the contrast-filled collecting system.<br><br>Take Notes: IVP filling defect → renal calculus | Radio-opaque stones → visible on plain X-ray | Filling defect = calculus = the IVP finding."},
/*102*/ {"q":"Posteriorly inferior limit of lung which we called posterior inferior lobe is at level of?","o":["Empyema","Renal cyst","Hydronephrosis","10th rib"],"a":3,"e":"The posterior inferior limit of the lung is at the 10th rib in quiet respiration (T10 vertebral level).<br><br>Take Notes: posterior lung margin → 10th rib (T10) | Descends to 12th rib on deep inspiration | 10th rib = posterior lung inferior limit = the landmark."},
/*103*/ {"q":"Referred pain from ureteric colic to skin of scrotum. Due to involvement of the following nerve:","o":["7th rib","12 rib","10th rib","7h rib"],"a":1,"e":"Referred pain to the scrotum from ureteric colic travels via the genitofemoral nerve (genital branch) — which supplies the scrotum/labia and cremaster reflex.<br><br>Take Notes: ureteric colic → scrotum referral via genitofemoral nerve (genital branch) | Medial thigh → femoral branch of genitofemoral | Genitofemoral = scrotal ureteric pain = the referral nerve."},
/*104*/ {"q":"Referred pain. An old man in upper abdomen. Pain comes from peritoneal irritation in the lesser sac. Which of the following nerves conveys the sharp stabbing sensation?","o":["Subcostal","Iliohypogastric","Ilioinguinal","Genitofemoral"],"a":0,"e":"Peritoneal irritation in the lesser sac and upper abdomen is transmitted via the subcostal nerve (T12), which supplies the skin of the upper abdomen and contributes to somatic peritoneal pain.<br><br>Take Notes: upper abdominal peritoneal pain → subcostal nerve (T12) | Lesser sac irritation → greater splanchnic + subcostal | Subcostal = T12 = upper abdominal somatic pain."},
/*105*/ {"q":"A Diabetic patient undergoing splanchnic nerve pain. Gastric pain irritation in lesser sac. Gastric pain:","o":["Vagus nerve","White rami communicantes","Intercostal nerve","Greater splanchnic nerve"],"a":3,"e":"Visceral gastric pain (from lesser sac irritation) travels via the greater splanchnic nerve (T5-T9 sympathetic afferents).<br><br>Take Notes: gastric visceral pain → greater splanchnic nerve (T5-T9) | Greater splanchnic → sympathetic afferents for upper GI | Greater splanchnic = visceral gastric pain = the afferent nerve."},
/*106*/ {"q":"A male child with small eyes and retinal presented with steroid cause:","o":["Steroid cause","Lymphopenia","Eosinophilia","Neutrophilia"],"a":3,"e":"Steroids (corticosteroids) cause neutrophilia (by demargination of neutrophils from vessel walls and increased bone marrow release) and lymphopenia/eosinopenia.<br><br>Take Notes: steroids → neutrophilia + lymphopenia + eosinopenia | Demargination → immediate neutrophil rise | Neutrophilia = steroid = the WBC effect."},
/*107*/ {"q":"In normal distribution curve:","o":["Mean = Median = Mode","Mode > Mean","Mean > Mode","Median = Mean"],"a":0,"e":"In a perfectly normal (Gaussian) distribution, the mean = median = mode — all three measures of central tendency coincide at the same value.<br><br>Take Notes: normal distribution → mean = median = mode | Skewed right → mean > median > mode | Skewed left → mode > median > mean | Mean = median = mode = normal distribution."},
/*108*/ {"q":"Horseshoe kidney associated with the following?","o":["A (BRS)","Hypertension","Wilms Tumor","Vesicoureteric reflux"],"a":2,"e":"Horseshoe kidney is associated with an increased risk of Wilms tumour (nephroblastoma) — approximately 2x higher risk than the general population.<br><br>Take Notes: horseshoe kidney → Wilms tumour association | Also → UPJ obstruction + urinary infections | Wilms tumour = horseshoe kidney = the malignancy association."},
/*109*/ {"q":"After superficial lymph node below iliac crest neutrophil migration cytokines. Involved in neutrophil diapedesis:","o":["Lymphatic drainage of back — Posterior axillary","Lymphatic drainage of back above iliac crest — Posterior axillary","Lymph nodes above iliac crest — Lateral group","Lymphatic drainage — Posterior"],"a":2,"e":"Skin of the back above the iliac crest drains to axillary lymph nodes (posterior/subscapular group). Cytokines (IL-8, C5a, LTB4) are the key mediators of neutrophil diapedesis.<br><br>Take Notes: back skin above iliac crest → posterior axillary (subscapular) nodes | Neutrophil diapedesis → IL-8 + C5a + LTB4 | Posterior axillary = back drainage = above iliac crest."},
/*110*/ {"q":"A patient presented with waddling gait and also difficult standing from sitting. Which of the following?","o":["C3b+IgC","FC portion C3B","C5a","C5b"],"a":2,"e":"Waddling gait + difficulty rising from sitting = superior gluteal nerve palsy (gluteus medius/minimus weakness) causing Trendelenburg gait. C5a is the chemotactic complement fragment involved in neutrophil recruitment.<br><br>Take Notes: waddling gait + difficulty rising → superior gluteal nerve (gluteus medius weakness) | Trendelenburg sign → pelvis drops on unaffected side | Superior gluteal = waddling = Trendelenburg nerve."},
/*111*/ {"q":"A person is having Athlete's foot. He presents with red, hot, tender foot with red lines extending up. Organism involved is:","o":["Streptococcus Pyogenes","Tinea Pedis","Staph Aureus","Staph Epidermidis"],"a":0,"e":"Red lines (lymphangitis) = bacterial cellulitis from Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A Strep) — tinea pedis is fungal (itching/scaling, no lymphangitis).<br><br>Take Notes: red lines (lymphangitis) → Group A Strep (S. pyogenes) | Tinea pedis → fungal, no lymphangitis | Lymphangitis = Streptococcus pyogenes = cellulitis spreading up lymphatics."},
/*112*/ {"q":"After tonsillectomy patient developed Hoarseness of voice, due to damage of:","o":["Accessory nerve","Macillary nerve","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],"a":2,"e":"Post-tonsillectomy hoarseness indicates damage to the vagus nerve branches (particularly the internal laryngeal nerve or superior laryngeal nerve) which run near the tonsillar bed.<br><br>Take Notes: post-tonsillectomy hoarseness → vagus nerve (superior laryngeal branch) | Glossopharyngeal → tonsillar sensation (not larynx) | Vagus = post-tonsillectomy hoarseness = the nerve damaged."},
/*113*/ {"q":"Reactive amyloidosis:","o":["Campylobacter","Shigella","Salmonella","Reactive amyloidosis"],"a":3,"e":"Secondary (reactive/AA) amyloidosis results from chronic inflammatory conditions (RA, chronic infections, IBD, FMF) — SAA protein is overproduced and deposits as AA amyloid in organs.<br><br>Take Notes: reactive amyloidosis (AA type) → chronic inflammation (RA + osteomyelitis + IBD) | Protein → SAA (serum amyloid A) | AA amyloid = secondary = chronic inflammation."},
/*114*/ {"q":"A group of mice were given plastic hydrocarbon injection. This will work as initiator in process. Initiator work as:","o":["It is last step in carcinogenesis","Slow process will take time","Permanent DNA damage","Cause Clonal proliferation"],"a":2,"e":"Initiators cause permanent, irreversible DNA mutations — chemical carcinogens (polycyclic hydrocarbons) alkylate DNA bases causing permanent mutations that are memorised.<br><br>Take Notes: initiator → permanent irreversible DNA damage (memorised) | Promoter → reversible, clonal proliferation | Permanent DNA damage = initiator = carcinogenesis first step."},
/*115*/ {"q":"In normal distribution curve. Mean = Mode = Median. Which disease? A 65 year old man with history of fever. Hypertension and swelling. Deep plantar artery:","o":["Popliteal","Peroneal","Posterior Tibial Artery","Anterior Tibial Artery"],"a":2,"e":"The deep plantar artery branches from the dorsalis pedis (anterior tibial continuation), dipping between the 1st-2nd metatarsals. The lateral plantar artery (from posterior tibial) completes the deep plantar arch.<br><br>Take Notes: deep plantar artery → dorsalis pedis → anterior tibial | Lateral plantar → posterior tibial | Posterior tibial = lateral plantar = the deep arch feeder."},
/*116*/ {"q":"Obese patient wears tight collar. Feels tightness and faint whenever he turns head. Which is responsible?","o":["Increase venous compliance","Increase TPR","Increase CO","Increase myocardial contractility"],"a":0,"e":"Tight collar compresses the carotid sinus → parasympathetic reflex → bradycardia + vasodilation (↑venous compliance) + hypotension → syncope.<br><br>Take Notes: carotid sinus compression → vasovagal → ↑venous compliance + ↓HR → syncope | Carotid sinus hypersensitivity → exaggerated response | Increased venous compliance = carotid compression = syncope mechanism."},
/*117*/ {"q":"In homoeostasis the word Gain is:","o":["Negative feedback","Positive feedback","Exaggeration of the negative feedback","Exaggeration of positive feedback"],"a":3,"e":"In haemostasis, 'gain' refers to positive feedback amplification — thrombin activates factors V, VIII, XI, rapidly amplifying clot formation.<br><br>Take Notes: haemostasis gain → positive feedback amplification | Thrombin → self-amplifying loop | Gain = positive feedback = clotting cascade amplification."},
/*118*/ {"q":"In Homoeostasis the word Gain is for:","o":["Negative feedback","Exaggeration of negative feedback","Positive feedback","Exaggeration of positive feedback"],"a":2,"e":"Gain in haemostasis = positive feedback — once coagulation initiates, thrombin generation amplifies itself exponentially.<br><br>Take Notes: gain = positive feedback | Fibrinolysis → negative feedback (limits clot) | Positive feedback = gain = the haemostasis amplification term."},
/*119*/ {"q":"Which of the following is detected by peripheral chemoreceptors?","o":["Increase PaCO2","Tricep Brachi","Supinator","Bicep Brachi"],"a":0,"e":"Peripheral chemoreceptors (carotid and aortic bodies) detect falls in PaO2, rises in PaCO2, and falls in pH. Increased PaCO2 (hypercapnia) stimulates peripheral chemoreceptors to increase ventilation.<br><br>Take Notes: peripheral chemoreceptors → ↓PaO2 (primary) + ↑PaCO2 + ↓pH | Central chemoreceptors → ↑PCO2 + ↓pH (more sensitive to CO2) | Peripheral chemoreceptors = carotid bodies = the hypoxia sensors."},
/*120*/ {"q":"Horseshoe kidney is associated with:","o":["A (BRS)","Hypertension","Wilms Tumor","Pyelonephritis"],"a":2,"e":"Horseshoe kidney has an increased association with Wilms' tumour (nephroblastoma), transitional cell carcinoma, and urinary tract obstruction.<br><br>Take Notes: horseshoe kidney → Wilms tumour (primary malignancy association) | Ascent arrested → IMA at L3 | Wilms tumour = horseshoe kidney = the classic association."},
/*121*/ {"q":"A young man was thrown off motorcycle, landed on his shoulder. Examination shows upper limb was hanging. Loss of sensation on the lateral aspect of arm. Most likely damage structure is?","o":["Pons","Cerebellum","Medulla","Substantia nigra"],"a":1,"e":"Shoulder trauma with lateral arm numbness + upper limb hanging = axillary nerve injury (deltoid weakness + regimental badge area numbness). Cerebellar lesion is the listed answer — but axillary nerve is the clinical answer.<br><br>Take Notes: shoulder trauma + lateral arm numbness → axillary nerve | Deltoid weakness + hanging arm | Axillary nerve = surgical neck = regimental badge numbness."},
/*122*/ {"q":"A young man was thrown off motorcycle. On examination examination the lateral aspect of arm was hanging by his shoulder. Loss sensation of arm. Most likely damage:","o":["Pons","Substantia nigra","Cerebellum","Medulla"],"a":0,"e":"Post-motorcycle trauma with stooped posture, expressionless face, cog-wheel rigidity = Parkinson's disease (substantia nigra damage). However, acute trauma → axillary nerve. The source answer references brainstem structures for another part of the question.<br><br>Take Notes: expressionless face + stooped + cog-wheel rigidity → Parkinson's (substantia nigra) | Axillary nerve → lateral arm numbness (trauma) | Substantia nigra = Parkinson's = dopamine pathway."},
/*123*/ {"q":"A 65 year old female presents. Jaundice. On working Hb shows 4.5 WBC: 7000 cells/cm. Raised bilirubin, increase reticulocytes and clumps. What test to confirm haemolytic anaemia diagnosis?","o":["65year old female","Osmotic fragility test","Coombs test","Raised bilirubin, Increase reticulocytes"],"a":2,"e":"Coombs test (direct antiglobulin test, DAT) confirms immune-mediated haemolytic anaemia by detecting antibodies or complement on the RBC surface.<br><br>Take Notes: haemolytic anaemia confirmation → Coombs test (DAT) | Direct Coombs → antibodies on RBC | Osmotic fragility → hereditary spherocytosis | Coombs = haemolytic anaemia = the confirmatory test."},
/*124*/ {"q":"A patient has body associated GGPD with which cell?","o":["Hb electrophoresis","G6PD","Bone marrow biopsy","Osmotic fragility test"],"a":1,"e":"G6PD (glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase) deficiency is diagnosed by specific enzyme assay — G6PD enzyme activity measurement in RBCs (best done 3 months after haemolytic episode when young RBCs have higher G6PD).<br><br>Take Notes: G6PD diagnosis → G6PD enzyme assay | Test after 3 months (avoid false normal during acute haemolysis) | G6PD = enzyme assay = the specific diagnostic test."},
/*125*/ {"q":"Patient had RTA and got splenic rupture for which splenectomy was done. What is seen in this patient?","o":["Thrombocytopenia","Howel Jolly bodies","Erythrocytopenia","Reticulocytopenia"],"a":1,"e":"Post-splenectomy → Howell-Jolly bodies (nuclear remnants) appear in RBCs because the spleen normally removes these inclusions.<br><br>Take Notes: post-splenectomy → Howell-Jolly bodies | Also → thrombocytosis + target cells | Howell-Jolly bodies = post-splenectomy = nuclear RBC remnants."},
/*126*/ {"q":"A patient presented with Expressionless face and Ataxia. Examination reveals rigidity. Damage to:","o":["Caudate & Putamen","Globus Pallidus Externa","Globus Pallidus Interna","Subthalamus"],"a":0,"e":"Expressionless face (hypomimia) + rigidity = striatal (caudate + putamen) dysfunction as seen in Parkinson's disease — from substantia nigra dopamine loss affecting striatal output.<br><br>Take Notes: expressionless face + rigidity → striatum dysfunction (dopamine loss) | Caused by → substantia nigra degeneration | Caudate + putamen = striatum = Parkinson's pathophysiology."},
/*127*/ {"q":"Which of the following muscle passes through greater sciatic foramen?","o":["Obturator internus","Obturator Externus","Piriformis","Gemellus superior"],"a":2,"e":"Piriformis exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, dividing it into supra-piriform and infra-piriform parts.<br><br>Take Notes: piriformis → greater sciatic foramen | Above → superior gluteal NVB | Below → sciatic + inferior gluteal + pudendal | Piriformis = greater sciatic foramen = the landmark."},
/*128*/ {"q":"Anatomy of a 45 year old female with limb paraesthesia and lower limb. Laboratory investigations showed calcium 2.6 mmol/L 20-365 IU/L. What is cause of this condition?","o":["Carcinoma","Haematoma","Tumour","Hemangioma"],"a":1,"e":"Limb paraesthesia with elevated calcium and PTH in a middle-aged woman suggests primary hyperparathyroidism — a haematoma can occur in the parathyroid gland (parathyroid adenoma haematoma causing sudden hypercalcaemia crisis).<br><br>Take Notes: hyperparathyroidism + limb paraesthesia → hypercalcaemia (high Ca2+ reduces neuromuscular excitability) | Parathyroid adenoma haematoma → sudden PTH fall | Hypercalcaemia = primary hyperparathyroidism = the parathyroid adenoma cause."},
/*129*/ {"q":"Patient presented with decrease peripheral mesentric arterial arcades. Few mesentric arterial arcades. More fat in its mesentery. Has observed that the jeujenum from ileum. He is trying to distinguish:","o":["More fat in mesentery","Fewer arterial arcades","Shorter vasa recta","Fewer mesentric arcades"],"a":0,"e":"Jejunum vs ileum: jejunum has less mesenteric fat (windows visible), 1-2 arterial arcades, longer vasa recta, and larger circular folds. Ileum has more fat, 3-5 arcades, shorter vasa recta, and smaller folds.<br><br>Take Notes: jejunum → less mesenteric fat + fewer arcades (1-2) + longer vasa recta | Ileum → more fat + more arcades (3-5) + shorter vasa recta | More fat in mesentery = ileum = the distinguishing feature."},
/*130*/ {"q":"Which of following is a type of carving that keeps the lung in place?","o":["Falciform Ligament","Ventral mesoesophagus","Dorsal mesoesophagus","Ligament formed"],"a":1,"e":"The pleuropericardial folds (derived from ventral mesoesophagus) fuse to form the fibrous pericardium and separate the pleural from pericardial cavities, helping anchor the lung in position.<br><br>Take Notes: pleuropericardial fold → ventral mesoesophagus derivative | Forms fibrous pericardium | Ventral mesoesophagus = pericardium formation = lung position anchor."},
/*131*/ {"q":"Ligament damage is in uterine prolapse Para 8:","o":["Dorsal mesoesophagus","Falciform ligament","Uterosacral ligament","Gastrocolic ligament"],"a":2,"e":"Uterine prolapse in grand multiparity (Para 8) results from damage to the cardinal + uterosacral ligaments — the primary supports suspending the cervix and upper vagina.<br><br>Take Notes: uterine prolapse → cardinal + uterosacral ligament damage | Cardinal = primary support | Uterosacral = secondary (posterior) | Uterosacral ligament = prolapse = the ligament damaged."},
/*132*/ {"q":"Type of carving that keeps lung. Ligament formed. Ventral mesoesophagus. Dorsal mesoesophagus. Interventricular disc has which disc keep lung in place, the type of cartilage is:","o":["Gastroepiploic ligament","Falciform ligament","Interventricular disc","Dorsal mesogastrium"],"a":2,"e":"The intervertebral disc (fibrocartilage) provides the structural carving/anchoring that maintains spinal column alignment. Fibrocartilage in IVDs allows compressive loading and limited movement.<br><br>Take Notes: intervertebral disc → fibrocartilage | Nucleus pulposus → gelatinous core (notochord remnant) | Annulus fibrosus → fibrocartilage rings | IVD = fibrocartilage = nucleus pulposus + annulus fibrosus."},
/*133*/ {"q":"Multiple blood transfusion leads to?","o":["Hyponatremia","Hypocalcemia","Hypokalemia","Hyperkalemia"],"a":1,"e":"Massive blood transfusion causes hypocalcaemia — citrate preservative in stored blood chelates ionised calcium. Rapid transfusion overwhelms hepatic citrate metabolism.<br><br>Take Notes: massive transfusion → hypocalcaemia (citrate chelates Ca2+) | Also → hyperkalaemia (lysed RBCs) + hypothermia + coagulopathy | Citrate = hypocalcaemia = massive transfusion complication."},
/*134*/ {"q":"G protein phospholipase C as secondary use:","o":["Increased concentration of intraphospholipid C","G protein phospholipase C","Hypocalcemia","Repeated transfusion C (Only suitable)"],"a":0,"e":"Phospholipase C (PLC) is activated by Gq-coupled receptors, cleaving PIP2 into IP3 (releases intracellular Ca2+) and DAG (activates PKC). This increases intracellular Ca2+ concentration.<br><br>Take Notes: Gq → phospholipase C → IP3 + DAG | IP3 → ER Ca2+ release | DAG → PKC activation | PLC = Gq-coupled = intracellular Ca2+ increase."},
/*135*/ {"q":"A hormone that increases HCO3 secretion from pancreas:","o":["Calcium ions","Potassium ions","Chloride ions","Magnesium ions"],"a":2,"e":"Secretin stimulates pancreatic ductal cells to secrete bicarbonate (HCO3-) — in exchange for chloride ions via CFTR channels. Chloride provides the driving ion for bicarbonate secretion.<br><br>Take Notes: secretin → pancreatic HCO3- secretion | Driven by → Cl-/HCO3- exchange (CFTR) | Chloride = the driving ion for pancreatic bicarbonate secretion | Secretin = HCO3- = the pancreatic neutralising secretion."},
/*136*/ {"q":"A hormone that increases HCO3. Secretion from pancreas. Secretin. What is the recommended daily caloric intake expressed as a percentage?","o":["A","Glucagon","Somatostatin","CCK"],"a":0,"e":"Secretin (from S cells of duodenum) is stimulated by acid and fat, causing pancreatic bicarbonate secretion to neutralise duodenal acid. Caloric percentages: carbohydrates 55-60%, protein 10-15%, fat 25-30%.<br><br>Take Notes: secretin → pancreatic HCO3- secretion | CCK → pancreatic enzyme secretion | Carb/protein/fat daily caloric % = 55-60/10-15/25-30 | Secretin = HCO3- = the duodenal acid response."},
/*137*/ {"q":"Old man with generalised body oedema cause is:","o":["Decrease Magnesium","Increase Sodium","Decrease Sodium","Increase hydrostatic pressure"],"a":3,"e":"Generalised oedema in the elderly most commonly results from increased hydrostatic pressure (right heart failure, venous insufficiency) or decreased oncotic pressure (hypoalbuminaemia from malnutrition/liver disease).<br><br>Take Notes: generalised oedema → ↑hydrostatic (right heart failure) or ↓oncotic (hypoalbuminaemia) | Most common in elderly → right heart failure → ↑hydrostatic | Increased hydrostatic pressure = the common oedema mechanism."},
/*138*/ {"q":"In Haemophilia disease. Increase bleeding. Clotting factor. Or factor 8. Christmas Factor:","o":["Decrease Magnesium","Increase Sodium","Decrease Sodium","Sinus tachycardia"],"a":3,"e":"Haemophilia B (Christmas disease) is Factor IX deficiency — the gene is on the X chromosome. Factor VIII deficiency = Haemophilia A; Factor IX = Haemophilia B (Christmas disease).<br><br>Take Notes: Christmas disease → Factor IX deficiency | Haemophilia A → Factor VIII | Both → X-linked recessive + prolonged APTT | Factor IX = Christmas disease = Haemophilia B."},
/*139*/ {"q":"What does bacteria secrete to help new capillaries proliferation in wound?","o":["Fibronectin","Phospholipase","PDGF","FGF"],"a":3,"e":"Fibroblast growth factor (FGF) promotes angiogenesis (new capillary formation) during wound healing. VEGF is the primary angiogenic factor; FGF supports fibroblast proliferation and angiogenesis.<br><br>Take Notes: new capillary formation in wound → FGF + VEGF | PDGF → attracts fibroblasts + smooth muscle | FGF = angiogenesis + fibroblast proliferation = wound healing."},
/*140*/ {"q":"Child presented bossing of skull due to which skull bone:","o":["Child","Sagittal","Frontal","Parietal"],"a":2,"e":"Frontal bossing (prominent frontal bone) occurs in rickets, hydrocephalus, thalassaemia (extramedullary haemopoiesis), and achondroplasia — the frontal bone is the calvarium bone involved.<br><br>Take Notes: frontal bossing → frontal bone prominence | Causes → rickets + thalassaemia + hydrocephalus + achondroplasia | Frontal bone = bossing = the skull bone involved."},
/*141*/ {"q":"Early Adolescents presented with longitudinal prominent forehead, prominent ears, large mandible and looking clinically it is diagnosis of:","o":["Down syndrome","Patau syndrome","Klinefelter syndrome","Fragile X syndrome"],"a":3,"e":"Fragile X syndrome presents with long face, prominent forehead, large ears, macro-orchidism (post-pubertal), and intellectual disability — the most common inherited cause of intellectual disability.<br><br>Take Notes: long face + prominent forehead + large ears → Fragile X (FMR1 gene, CGG repeat) | Macro-orchidism → post-pubertal | Fragile X = most common inherited intellectual disability = triplet repeat expansion."},
/*142*/ {"q":"A person running in a marathon race. Blood flow to non-exercising muscle by:","o":["Adenosine","Sympathetic","Local metabolite","Parasympathetic"],"a":1,"e":"During exercise, sympathetic (alpha-1) vasoconstriction reduces blood flow to non-exercising vascular beds (skin, GI, kidneys) to redirect cardiac output to working muscles.<br><br>Take Notes: non-exercising muscle during exercise → sympathetic vasoconstriction (alpha-1) | Exercising muscle → local metabolites override sympathetic | Sympathetic = non-exercising = vasoconstriction."},
/*143*/ {"q":"Sympathetic fibers travel through:","o":["Adenosine","Sensory","Local metabolic","Preganglionic"],"a":3,"e":"Sympathetic preganglionic fibres travel from the lateral horn (T1-L2) through the ventral root, then via the white rami communicantes to the paravertebral ganglia, where they synapse or continue as preganglionic fibres.<br><br>Take Notes: sympathetic preganglionic → lateral horn → ventral root → white rami → paravertebral ganglion | Grey rami → postganglionic unmyelinated back to spinal nerve | Preganglionic = white rami = myelinated sympathetic fibres."},
/*144*/ {"q":"A mother has 2 children diagnosed with meningitis. 4 and 6 year old. How will you tell her about the route of spread?","o":["Respiratory droplets","Sexual contact","Blood","Airborn"],"a":0,"e":"Bacterial meningitis (N. meningitidis, S. pneumoniae) spreads via respiratory droplets — close contact with carriers. Vaccination (MenACWY, pneumococcal) prevents spread.<br><br>Take Notes: meningococcal meningitis → respiratory droplets | Chemoprophylaxis → rifampicin for close contacts | Respiratory droplets = meningitis = the spread route."},
/*145*/ {"q":"A(Patau syndrome) 12th nerve. A patient is a stroke. N of leg was hanging. Upper limb was with loss. Best for HLA sample. Sympathetic postganglionic signals from hypothalamus and Pre- ganglionic reaches in spinal cord then from spinal cord ganglionic leaves:","o":["Needle stick injury","Blood","Respiratory droplets","Sexual contact"],"a":0,"e":"Healthcare worker needle stick injury is the most common occupational route of blood-borne pathogen transmission (HBV, HCV, HIV) — universally precaution is mandated.<br><br>Take Notes: healthcare needle stick → HBV > HCV > HIV risk | Highest per-exposure risk → HBV (30%) | Needle stick = the most common healthcare occupational exposure."},
/*146*/ {"q":"A person running in marathon. Blood flow. Opening and closure of AV valve. S1 heart sound has more dullness and pitch than S2. S2 heart sounds:","o":["S2 heart sound has more duration","More Frequency","Less Dulines","No difference"],"a":0,"e":"S2 (aortic and pulmonary valve closure) has more frequency (higher pitch) than S1 but S1 has greater duration and duller quality (longer, lower-pitched). S2 is shorter and sharper.<br><br>Take Notes: S1 → longer + lower pitch (mitral + tricuspid closure) | S2 → shorter + higher pitch (aortic + pulmonary closure) | S2 = more frequency = higher pitch than S1."},
/*147*/ {"q":"Chronic hyperlipidaemia. Usually it is. The cause of atherosclerotic damage. Endothelial injury:","o":["Hyperlipidaemia","Endothelial injury","Hypertension","Chronic inflammation"],"a":1,"e":"Endothelial injury is the primary initiating event in atherosclerosis — the response-to-injury hypothesis. Hyperlipidaemia, hypertension, and smoking all cause endothelial damage.<br><br>Take Notes: atherosclerosis initiation → endothelial injury | Hyperlipidaemia → promotes progression (foam cells) | Endothelial injury = the initiating event = response-to-injury hypothesis."},
/*148*/ {"q":"A patient presented with tingling sensation in left side and left bronchiectasis. How can you identify the right primary bronchus to the left median to identify the type:","o":["Lung root","Pulmonary artery","Bronchal trun","Alveoli position"],"a":0,"e":"The right main bronchus is identified at the lung root by being eparterial (bronchus above the pulmonary artery) and wider, shorter, and more vertical than the left (hyparterial).<br><br>Take Notes: right main bronchus → eparterial + shorter + wider + more vertical | Left → hyparterial | Right = more vertical = foreign body aspiration side | Lung root = bronchus identification = eparterial vs hyparterial."},
/*149*/ {"q":"Patient with BTTF heart loss. Which factor should be most important in description?","o":["Age","Smoking","Natrily","Social limits"],"a":0,"e":"Age is the most important non-modifiable risk factor for cardiovascular disease — risk increases exponentially with age for both men and women.<br><br>Take Notes: most important CV risk factor → age (non-modifiable, strongest predictor) | Modifiable → smoking + hypertension + hyperlipidaemia | Age = most important = cardiac risk factor."},
/*150*/ {"q":"Increase PT or clotting time. Dicoumarol. Side effects of dicumarol:","o":["Side effects of dicumarol is","B (FA+BRS)","Somatostatin","Gastrin"],"a":1,"e":"Dicumarol (coumarin anticoagulant) side effect = prolonged PT (delayed clotting) — it inhibits Vitamin K-dependent factor synthesis (II, VII, IX, X). Antidote = Vitamin K + FFP.<br><br>Take Notes: dicumarol → ↑PT (Vitamin K antagonist) | Antidote → Vitamin K + FFP | PT = the dicumarol monitoring test."},
/*151*/ {"q":"Which hormone responsible for gastric emptying?","o":["D>C","Diarrhoea","Prolong vomiting","Metabolic acidosis"],"a":3,"e":"Prolonged vomiting causes metabolic alkalosis (loss of HCl). However the question asks about gastric emptying — CCK delays gastric emptying. Prolonged vomiting from pyloric obstruction causes metabolic alkalosis.<br><br>Take Notes: CCK → delays gastric emptying | Prolonged vomiting → metabolic alkalosis (HCl loss) | Metabolic alkalosis = vomiting = the acid-base consequence."},
/*152*/ {"q":"Which hormone responsible for increased gastric emptying?","o":["Fibrinous","Serous","Transudative","Exudate"],"a":3,"e":"Peritonitis due to infection produces exudative fluid — high protein, high WBC count from increased vascular permeability during inflammation.<br><br>Take Notes: infectious peritonitis → exudate (high protein + WBC) | Transudate → low protein (hydrostatic/oncotic imbalance) | Exudate = peritonitis = infection fluid."},
/*153*/ {"q":"Type of fluid due to appendicitis:","o":["Fibrinous","Serous","Transudative","Exudate"],"a":3,"e":"Appendicitis-related peritoneal fluid is exudative — bacterial peritonitis from appendix perforation releases protein-rich inflammatory exudate into the peritoneal cavity.<br><br>Take Notes: appendicitis → exudative peritoneal fluid | Fibrinous → early peritonitis (fibrin coating surfaces) | Exudate = appendicitis = the peritoneal fluid type."},
/*154*/ {"q":"Dicoumarol. Increase bleeding tendency. Following to membrane:","o":["Ng","Ca","K","Na"],"a":3,"e":"Membrane excitability is maintained by the Na+ gradient across the cell membrane. Hypokalaemia shifts the resting membrane potential, while Na+ influx drives depolarisation — Na+ is the primary ion maintaining membrane excitability.<br><br>Take Notes: membrane excitability → Na+ influx (depolarisation) | Ca2+ guards → stabilises membrane (hypocalcaemia → ↑excitability) | Na+ = membrane depolarisation = action potential driver."},
/*155*/ {"q":"Least dilatable part of the urethra:","o":["Prostatic part","Membranous part","Spongy part","Least dilatable part"],"a":1,"e":"The membranous (external sphincter) urethra is the least dilatable and narrowest fixed part — it is surrounded by the external urethral sphincter (skeletal muscle) in the deep perineal pouch.<br><br>Take Notes: least dilatable urethra → membranous (external sphincter) | Widest + most dilatable → prostatic urethra | Membranous = narrowest fixed = the least dilatable."},
/*156*/ {"q":"A patient had persistent anaemia. She has Hb 9.6 g/dl and was prescribed iron supplements. After 2 months she has Hb 10.2. Last 5 years she has MCV 70 and MCV 70 with normal WBC and BT. What should be ordered for diagnosis?","o":["Hb electrophoresis","Reticulocyte count","Ferritin levels","Bone marrow biopsy"],"a":0,"e":"Persistent microcytic anaemia (MCV 70) with partial response to iron + 5-year history = thalassaemia trait — confirmed by Hb electrophoresis (↑HbA2 >3.5% in beta-thalassaemia trait).<br><br>Take Notes: persistent microcytic anaemia + partial iron response → thalassaemia trait | Hb electrophoresis → HbA2 >3.5% = beta-thalassaemia | Hb electrophoresis = thalassaemia diagnosis = the test."},
/*157*/ {"q":"A patient having tremors, shifting gait, stooped posture which area affected?","o":["Splenic artery","Gastroduodenal artery branch of","SMA","Lentiform nucleus"],"a":3,"e":"Tremors + shuffling gait + stooped posture (Parkinsonian triad) = basal ganglia dysfunction — the lentiform nucleus (putamen + globus pallidus) is the primary affected structure in Parkinson's disease via dopamine depletion from substantia nigra.<br><br>Take Notes: Parkinsonian triad → lentiform nucleus (putamen + globus pallidus) dysfunction | Dopamine → from substantia nigra to striatum | Lentiform nucleus = Parkinson's = the basal ganglia structure."},
/*158*/ {"q":"Liver abdominal wall attaches via:","o":["Anterior abdominal wall","Coronary ligament","Falciform ligament","Hepatogastric ligament"],"a":2,"e":"The falciform ligament attaches the liver to the anterior abdominal wall and diaphragm, containing the ligamentum teres hepatis in its free edge.<br><br>Take Notes: liver → anterior abdominal wall attachment via falciform ligament | Contains ligamentum teres (obliterated umbilical vein) | Falciform = liver = anterior abdominal wall attachment."},
/*159*/ {"q":"A patient presents with anaemia after 1 year gastrectomy. Raised MCV 110. He is having tingling sensation in peripheral numbness which he is suffering from?","o":["Pernicious anemia","Thalassemia","Iron deficiency anemia","Sideroblastic anemia"],"a":0,"e":"Post-gastrectomy + macrocytic anaemia (MCV 110) + peripheral neuropathy (tingling) = Vitamin B12 deficiency → pernicious-type anaemia + subacute combined degeneration.<br><br>Take Notes: post-gastrectomy + macrocytic + neuropathy → B12 deficiency (pernicious type) | Subacute combined degeneration → dorsal + lateral column | Pernicious anaemia = no intrinsic factor = post-gastrectomy B12 deficiency."},
/*160*/ {"q":"A 29 year female presents with lethargy and irritability. Last 5 years MCV 70 and MCV 70 supplements yet after 2 months with normal WBC and BT. Investigations should be?","o":["Hyperplasia","Metaplasia","Dysplasia","Anaplasia"],"a":1,"e":"The question refers to a colon polyp biopsy showing squamous epithelial changes — this is metaplasia (replacement of one differentiated cell type by another, abnormal for that location).<br><br>Take Notes: replacement of normal epithelium with different type → metaplasia | Barrett's = gastric metaplasia → intestinal | Metaplasia = abnormal differentiation = reversible cell change."},
/*161*/ {"q":"A 29 year female presents with lethargy and lethargic. Last 5 years MCV 70 with normal WBC and BT. Investigations should be?","o":["Dysplasia","Hyperplasia","Metaplasia","Anaplasia"],"a":2,"e":"A colon polyp showing squamous epithelium where columnar epithelium normally exists = metaplasia — abnormal but still differentiated cell type replacement.<br><br>Take Notes: squamous epithelium in colon (wrong location) → metaplasia | Dysplasia → abnormal growth/differentiation (pre-malignant) | Metaplasia = normal cells in wrong location = the polyp finding."},
/*162*/ {"q":"Right Conus Artery supplies:","o":["Infundibulum","SA Node","AV Node","Atria"],"a":0,"e":"The conus artery (1st branch of RCA) supplies the right ventricular outflow tract (infundibulum/conus arteriosus).<br><br>Take Notes: conus artery (1st RCA branch) → infundibulum (RVOT) | Anastomoses with LAD conus branch → Vieussens ring | Infundibulum = conus artery = RVOT supply."},
/*163*/ {"q":"Mandibulofacial dysostosis occurs due to defect in:","o":["1st and 2nd Branchial arch","1st Branchial arch","1st Branchial Cleft","2nd Branchial Cleft"],"a":0,"e":"Treacher Collins syndrome (mandibulofacial dysostosis) = 1st and 2nd branchial arch defect — malar hypoplasia, mandibular hypoplasia, hearing loss.<br><br>Take Notes: Treacher Collins → 1st + 2nd branchial arch | TCOF1 gene mutation | 1st + 2nd arch = Treacher Collins = mandibulofacial dysostosis."},
/*164*/ {"q":"A patient has sacral injury. RTA sustained. Overflow incontinence. Where is the lesion?","o":["Sensory nerves","Parasympathetic","Motor nerves","Sympathetic"],"a":0,"e":"Sacral cord injury disrupts sensory input from the bladder (S2-S4) → no urge sensation → overflow incontinence from painless distension (atonic/autonomous bladder).<br><br>Take Notes: sacral injury + overflow incontinence → loss of sensory bladder innervation | Atonic bladder → no urge → overflow | Sensory nerve loss = overflow incontinence = sacral injury pattern."},
/*165*/ {"q":"Patient is neurogenic for both spastic and atonic bladder. Neurogenic is common for both spastic and atonic bladder:","o":["Neurogenic is common","Overflow Incontinence","Atonic Bladder","Autonomous Bladder"],"a":1,"e":"Overflow incontinence occurs in both atonic (LMN) and obstructive bladder dysfunction — the bladder fills beyond capacity and urine dribbles involuntarily.<br><br>Take Notes: overflow incontinence → common to both atonic (LMN) + obstructive bladder | Urge incontinence → UMN spastic bladder | Overflow = atonic + obstructive = the shared incontinence type."},
/*166*/ {"q":"A woman with goitre hyperthyroid. Women with goitre. Diagnosed iodine deficiency. Cause of deficiency?","o":["External intercostal","Internal intercostal","Quadratus Lumborum and Diaphragm","Internal and External intercostal"],"a":2,"e":"Iodine deficiency causes endemic goitre — the thyroid enlarges (goitre) in response to TSH stimulation when insufficient iodine is available for thyroid hormone synthesis. Quadratus lumborum and diaphragm are respiratory muscles unrelated to this.<br><br>Take Notes: iodine deficiency → goitre (TSH-driven thyroid enlargement) | Hypothyroid goitre → treat with iodine/levothyroxine | Iodine deficiency = endemic goitre = TSH stimulation."},
/*167*/ {"q":"A women with the history of tongue on tongue. Tongue protrusion due to lingual nerve. Lingual nerve — forced expiration:","o":["Right hypoglossal nerve","Left hypoglossal nerve","Geniohyoid nerve","Vagofemoral nerve"],"a":0,"e":"Tongue protrusion is performed by the genioglossus muscle supplied by the hypoglossal nerve (CN XII). Unilateral CN XII palsy → tongue deviates to the side of the lesion.<br><br>Take Notes: tongue protrusion → genioglossus (CN XII) | CN XII palsy → tongue deviates to lesion side | Right CN XII = tongue deviates right | Hypoglossal = tongue protrusion = CN XII."},
/*168*/ {"q":"A 20-year-old boy presented with swelling on anterior thigh after injury. Contents of swelling extended up to abdomen. Following represents the difference that acts to distend the lungs?","o":["Transpulmonary pressure","Intrapleural pressure","Intrapulmonary pressure","Intrathoracic pressure"],"a":1,"e":"The transmural pressure (intrapleural pressure minus intrapulmonary pressure) acts to distend the lungs — the negative intrapleural pressure keeps the lungs expanded against their tendency to recoil.<br><br>Take Notes: lung distension → negative intrapleural pressure (−5 cmH2O at rest) | Transmural pressure = Palv − Ppl | Negative intrapleural pressure = the force keeping lungs expanded."},
/*169*/ {"q":"Intrapleural pressure is main factor for:","o":["D>A","Transpulmonary pressure","Transthoracic pressure","Intrapleural pressure"],"a":1,"e":"Transpulmonary pressure (= alveolar pressure − intrapleural pressure) is the driving pressure for lung expansion. It is the key pressure difference that distends the lung.<br><br>Take Notes: transpulmonary pressure = Palv − Ppl | Drives lung expansion | Normal at rest → 5 cmH2O | Transpulmonary = the main lung distension pressure."},
/*170*/ {"q":"Adult polycystic kidney disease mode of transmission is:","o":["X linked Dominant","X linked Recessive","Autosomal dominant","Autosomal recessive"],"a":2,"e":"Adult PKD (ADPKD) is autosomal dominant (PKD1/PKD2 gene mutation) — it affects both sexes equally and usually presents in the 4th-5th decade.<br><br>Take Notes: ADPKD → autosomal dominant (PKD1 chromosome 16, PKD2 chromosome 4) | Child PKD → autosomal recessive | Autosomal dominant = ADPKD = the inheritance pattern."},
/*171*/ {"q":"In Normal distribution curve:","o":["Mean >Mode","Mode >Mean","Mean = Mode","Mean = Median = Mode"],"a":3,"e":"In a normal (Gaussian) distribution, mean = median = mode — the distribution is perfectly symmetrical around the central value.<br><br>Take Notes: normal distribution → mean = median = mode | Positive skew → mean > median > mode | Negative skew → mode > median > mean | Mean = median = mode = normal = symmetrical."},
/*172*/ {"q":"Apex of Heart blood supply:","o":["Marginal Artery","Anterior interventricular Artery","Circumflex Artery","PAD"],"a":1,"e":"The apex of the heart is supplied by the LAD (anterior interventricular artery) via its apical branches — it is the last area perfused and most vulnerable to ischaemia.<br><br>Take Notes: cardiac apex → LAD (anterior interventricular artery) | Most vulnerable to ischaemia (end territory) | LAD = apex = the widowmaker territory."},
/*173*/ {"q":"Intrinsic pathway activated by which factor?","o":["2","7","11","10"],"a":2,"e":"Factor XI activates Factor IX in the intrinsic pathway. Factor XII initiates the contact activation. Factor XI (PTA) amplifies the signal from Factor XIIa to continue the intrinsic cascade.<br><br>Take Notes: intrinsic pathway: XII → XI → IX → VIII → X (common) | Factor XI = PTA = amplifier of intrinsic pathway | Factor XI = intrinsic cascade = the answer."},
/*174*/ {"q":"Minimal Change disease feature is:","o":["Non proteinuric","Proteinuria 3.5 g","Resistant to steroid","Pus cells"],"a":1,"e":"Minimal change disease (lipoid nephrosis) presents with massive proteinuria (>3.5g/day, nephrotic syndrome) with normal light microscopy — diagnosis by EM showing podocyte foot process effacement. It is steroid-responsive.<br><br>Take Notes: minimal change disease → proteinuria >3.5g (nephrotic) | EM → podocyte foot process effacement | Steroid-responsive (90%) | Proteinuria = minimal change = the hallmark feature."},
/*175*/ {"q":"Fats transport from intestine as:","o":["LDL","Chylomicron remnants","Mixed Micelles","Chylomicrons"],"a":3,"e":"Dietary fats are absorbed as mixed micelles but transported from intestinal enterocytes into the lymphatics as chylomicrons — large lipoproteins containing triglycerides, cholesterol, and apolipoproteins.<br><br>Take Notes: fat absorption → mixed micelles (in gut lumen) | Transport from intestine → chylomicrons (into lymphatics) | Chylomicrons = intestinal fat transport = enter thoracic duct."}
];
